XXVI. 1 Nor in these matters is anything changed by the insti- tuted Law of N ations3 excepting this only, that if an inequality of the contributions be agreed upon, this, where there is neither false decla- ration nor reticence of what ought to have been said, is in exterior actions held for equality. And thus, as by the Civil Law before Dio- cletian there was no action before a court of law for such inequality, so now among those who arc connected only by the Law of Nations, there is no demand or compulsion allowed on that account.
